column1: # executed_on: 'Darwin-21.6.0-Darwin Kernel Version 21.6.0: Mon Aug 22 20:19:52 PDT

column8: predicted_definition

column2: X-linked intellectual disability due to GRIA3 anomalies
column8: An X-linked intellectual disability characterized by moderate intellectual disability with variable occurrence of asthenic body habitus, dysmorphic features, autistic features, macrocephaly, seizures, myoclonic jerks, and hyporeflexia that is caused by anomalies in the GRIA3 gene on chromosome Xq25.
A syndrome that is characterized by an obstruction of the extrahepatic bile ducts within the liver. It often presents soon after birth with persistent jaundice and acholic stools.
An instance of multiple congenital anomalies/dysmorphic syndrome that is lethal.

column2: fatal infantile hypertrophic cardiomyopathy due to mitochondrial complex I deficiency
column8: Fatal infantile hypertrophic cardiomyopathy due to mitochondrial complex I deficiency is a severe form of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that presents in early infancy and is characterized by profound cardiac hypertrophy, heart failure, and early mortality.

column3: A new leukoencephalopathy, the CACH syndrome (Childhood Ataxia with Central nervous system Hypomyelination) or VWM (Vanishing White Matter) was identified on clinical and MRI criteria. Classically, this disease is characterized by (1) an onset between 2 and 5 years of age, with a cerebello-spastic syndrome exacerbated by episodes of fever or head trauma leading to death after 5 to 10 years of disease evolution, (2) a diffuse involvement of the white matter on cerebral MRI with a CSF-like signal intensity (cavitation), (3) a recessive autosomal mode of inheritance, (4) neuropathologic findings consistent with a cavitating orthochromatic leukodystrophy with increased number of oligodendrocytes with sometimes ``foamy'' aspect.
column8: A leukodystrophy that is characterized by the appearance of white matter of the brain with abnormally low density on CT scans and which has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in any one of the five genes: EIF2B1, EIF2B2, EIF2B3, EIF2B4, and EIF2B5 on chromosome 19q13

column3: Autosomal recessive form of complex hereditary spastic paraplegia.
column8: Autosomal recessive form of complex hereditary spastic paraplegia.

column3: A corneal dystrophy (disease) that is part of a larger syndrome.
column8: A syndromic corneal dystrophy.

column3: A rare combined T and B cell immunodeficiency with a predisposition to lymphoproliferative syndrome. It is characterized by persistent symptomatic EBV-viremia and hypogammaglobulinemia variably presenting with fever, lymphadenopathy and systemic inflammatory conditions including hepatitis, pneumonia and sepsis. It may be associated with lymphoma, hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis, and aplastic anemia.
column8: Lymphoproliferative disease that follows autosomal recessive inheritance pattern.
A dermatosis affecting the skin of the extremities and characterized by both hyperkeratosis and papillomatosis.

column2: anomaly of puberty or/and menstrual cycle
column8: An anomaly of the puberty or/and menstrual cycle in females.
A form of acrodysostosis characterized by multiple endocrine abnormalities including resistance to multiple hormones such as parathyroid hormone, thyroid-stimulating hormone, and growth hormone.

column2: 46,XX disorder of sex development induced by maternal-derived androgen
column8: 46,XX disorder of sex development induced by maternal-derived androgen is a rare, genetic disorder of sex development characterized by virilization of the external genitalia in a genetic female as a result of excess androgen exposure during prenatal development. This excess androgen exposure is typically derived from the mother, either through maternal hyperandrogenism or by exposure to exogenous androgens. It can result in a wide range of genital anomalies, from clitoromegaly and partial fusion of the labioscrotal folds to complete masculinization of the external genitalia. Internal reproductive structures are typically female, although mullerian anomalies can occur.
Myopathy characterized by the presence of caps or structures made of part of the plasma membrane of muscle fibers

column2: intestinal disease due to vitamin absorption anomaly
column8: A rare intestinal disease that has its basis in the disruption of intestinal absorption and vitamin transport.
A rare type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma that primarily affects the skin and can be aggressive in nature. It is characterized by the presence of malignant B lymphocytes in the skin. -- 2004

Teratogenic Pierre Robin syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that is characterized by the triad of micrognathia (abnormally small jaw), glossoptosis (falling back of the tongue), and cleft palate. This syndrome can result from exposure to certain teratogenic drugs or environmental factors during pregnancy.

Autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 85 is a neurodegenerative disorder characterized by early-onset spastic paraplegia, progressive cognitive decline, and dysmorphic facial features. Additional features may include seizures, optic atrophy, and hearing loss. The exact cause of the condition is currently unknown.

column2: progressive myoclonic epilepsy with neuroserpin inclusion bodies
column8: Progressive myoclonic epilepsy with neuroserpin inclusion bodies is a type of progressive myoclonic epilepsy characterized by the presence of neuroserpin inclusion bodies in the brain.
A tumor composed of neurons or arising from neuronal tissues.
Anomalies or variations of the normal eyelid border.

column2: congenital muscular dystrophy with cerebellar involvement
column8: A form of congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by cerebellar involvement, hypotonia, dystrophic changes on skeletal muscle biopsy, absence of muscle-eye-brain involvement, normal cognition and speech acquisition, and absence of cerebellar involvement on neuroimaging.

column2: retinal ciliopathy due to mutation in the RPGR gene
column8: Any retinal ciliopathy in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the RPGR gene.
An inherited digestive tract tumor (neoplasm) that is a type of hereditary disease and involves the digestive system.
A genetic obesity disorder that is characterized by an excessive amount of body fat and additional clinical features associated with a specific syndrome.

column2: congenital absence/hypoplasia of fingers excluding thumb
column8: Congenital absence/hypoplasia of fingers excluding thumb is a rare, non-syndromic, terminal transverse limb reduction defect characterized by absence or underdevelopment of the fingers, excluding the thumb.
A tumor that originates in the peritoneum and is not a metastasis from another site.

column2: 46,XX disorder of sex development induced by androgens excess
column8: A disorder of sex development in which an individual with a 46,XX karyotype develops male external genitalia, secondary sexual characteristics, or both, as a result of exposure to excessive androgens during early gestation.

column2: retinal ciliopathy due to mutation in Usher gene
column8: A retinal ciliopathy caused by a mutation in a Usher gene.
A structural anomaly of the respiratory system or thorax.

column2: transposition of the great arteries and conotruncal cardiac anomaly
column8: A congenital heart malformation characterized by the abnormal development of the great arteries, resulting in the aorta arising from the right ventricle and the pulmonary artery arising from the left ventricle.

column3: A urogenital tract malformation that is part of a larger syndrome.
column8: A urogenital tract malformation that is part of a larger syndrome.

column3: An inherited metabolic disease that is has its basis in the disruption of glycerol metabolic process.
column8: An inherited disorder resulting from the disruption of glycerol metabolic process.

column2: qualitative or quantitative defects of myotilin
column8: Any qualitative or quantitative defects in the protein myotilin that result in neuromuscular diseases.

column3: A hypothyroidism that is part of a larger syndrome.
column8: A condition characterized by a deficient production of thyroid hormones with a syndromic presentation.

column2: anomaly of the secretory and excretory apparatus of the lacrimal system
column8: Anomaly of the secretory and excretory apparatus of the lacrimal system.
A disorder that is characterized by the impaired transport of ketone bodies, resulting in an abnormal metabolism of fatty acids and ketone bodies.
An anomaly of the major induction processes in the eye that has a basis in the disruption of lens induction in the camera-type eye.

Regional variant of Guillain-Barre syndrome is a rare form of Guillain-Barre syndrome with prominent bulbar weakness and facial nerve involvement. Patients may present with ophthalmoplegia, facial diplegia, bulbar palsy, or with a combination of these features.
A visceral malformation that is part of a larger syndrome involving the liver, biliary tract, pancreas, or spleen.
A acquired peripheral movement disorder.
An abnormality or abnormal structure of the esophagus.

column2: AP4-related intellectual disability and spastic paraplegia
column3: A disorder that presents with spastic paraplegia and intellectual disability in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the AP4B1 gene.
column8: A rare syndromic intellectual disability and spastic paraplegia caused by variations in the AP4 genes: AP4B1, AP4E1, AP4M1, and AP4S1. It is characterized by intellectual disability, spasticity, developmental delay, and often features such as microcephaly, epilepsy, and brain abnormalities.

column2: qualitative or quantitative defects of protein O-mannose beta1, 2N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase
column8: A qualitative or quantitative defect of protein O-mannose beta1, 2N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase.

column2: qualitative or quantitative defects of glucosamine (UDP-N-acetyl)-2-epimerase/N-acetylmannosamine kinase
column8: A disease characterized by deficiency of the enzyme that catalyzes the conversion of N-acetylglucosamine (GlcNAc) to N-acetylmanosamine (ManNAc) in the first step of sialic acid synthesis.

column3: An inflammatory disease involving a pathogenic inflammatory response in the brain.
column8: A disease characterized by inflammation of the brain.
A disorder characterized by asymmetric development of the structures that make up the face and the skull.

column2: 46,XY disorder of sex development due to isolated 17,20-lyase deficiency
column3: 46,XY disorder of sex development due to isolated 17,20-lyase deficiency is a rare disorder of sex development due to reduced 17,20-lyase activity that affects individuals with 46,XY karyotype and is characterized by ambiguous external genitalia, including micropenis, perineal hypospadias, bifid scrotum, cryptorchidism, and a blind vaginal pouch. Blood pressure and electrolytes are normal whilst hormonal investigations show normal basal and stimulated levels of cortisol, and low basal and stimulated androgen levels.
column8: A disorder of sex development characterized by male pseudohermaphroditism with abnormalities of the external male genitalia, including undervirilization of the external genitalia, microphallus, and cryptorchidism; gonads are testes and mullerian structures are absent.
